{"id":7342,"date":"2017-10-16T21:24:45","date_gmt":"2017-10-17T04:24:45","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/?p=7342"},"modified":"2017-10-16T21:24:45","modified_gmt":"2017-10-17T04:24:45","slug":"trout-mountain","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/16\/trout-mountain\/","title":{"rendered":"TROUT MOUNTAIN"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\"><em><strong>TROUT MOUNTAIN\u00a0 \u00a0<\/strong><\/em>2688m\u00a0 \u00a08819&#8242;<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\"><em>Trout Mountain, a handsome peak, stands out above the town of Trout Lake. Reginald W. Brock (GSC) was to 2480 meters on this peak in 1904, and may have climbed it.<\/em><\/span><\/p>\n<p>Difficulty:<br \/>\nElevation gain:<br \/>\nKey elevations:<br \/>\nDistance:<br \/>\nTime:<br \/>\nSeason:<br \/>\nAssess:<br \/>\nMap:\u00a0<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">82K\/12 Beaton<\/span><\/p>\n<p><strong>Drive<\/strong>:<\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><em>The probable FA was by the Topographical Survey, route unknown. Surveyed at 8819 feet. Topographical work for this area was done by H. Boyd in 1903-1907.<\/em><\/span> (GSC Memoir 161:15)<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\">1. <strong>South Ridge.<\/strong> Start from the northwest end of Trout Lake, and take roads (probably overgrown) to mining claims north of Trout Mountain\u00a0<\/span><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\">(Lucky Boy Mine). Bushwhack up the north ridge of the north outlier of the mountain, and climb to the east summit.\u00a0<\/span><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\">Descend nearly 300 meters and climb to the col between the south and west summits, and ascend the south ridge of the west summit. (III,3,s).<br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><em>FRA Karl Kast (Forest Ranger), 9\/1950.\u00a0<\/em><\/span><\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>Variation:<\/strong> Instead of climbing the east summit, drop off the ridge, contour to the basin and climb to the col between the east and west summits. As above, avoid the steep east ridge of the west (main) summit by going south. There is a small glacier in the basin.<br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><em>FA Wm. Fix, Lorna Ream, David Gnagey, 1971.<\/em><\/span><\/span><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>TROUT MOUNTAIN\u00a0 \u00a02688m\u00a0 \u00a08819&#8242; Trout Mountain, a handsome peak, stands out above the town of Trout Lake. Reginald W. Brock (GSC) was to 2480 meters on this peak in 1904, and may have climbed it. Difficulty: Elevation gain: Key elevations: &hellip; <a href=\"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/16\/trout-mountain\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"jetpack_post_was_ever_published":false,"_jetpack_newsletter_access":"","_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs":false,"_jetpack_newsletter_tier_id":0,"_jetpack_memberships_contains_paywalled_content":false,"_jetpack_memberships_contains_paid_content":false,"footnotes":"","jetpack_publicize_message":"","jetpack_publicize_feature_enabled":true,"jetpack_social_post_already_shared":true,"jetpack_social_options":{"image_generator_settings":{"template":"highway","default_image_id":0,"enabled":false},"version":2}},"categories":[1],"tags":[],"class_list":["post-7342","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","hentry","category-uncategorized"],"aioseo_notices":[],"jetpack_pub